ontation with natural forces. With the open sea, the rocky coastline, and the menacing presence of Vesuvius, the image of Naples, more than any other city in early modern times, is associated in the collective imagination with the forces of nature. Even the populace was interpreted as a force of nature. In this volume, art, literature, and science historians investigate the convergence of culture and nature in a unique geographic context.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aArt, ModernxHistory. 0aArtszItalyzNaplesxHistory. 0aNature (Aesthetics) 4aArchitektur. 4aKunst. 4aNatur. 4aNeapel. 7aART / History / Renaissance.2bisacsh  aNature.  aNeapel.  aarchitecture.  aarts.1 aBarreto, Joana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCavi, Sabina de, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCocco, Sean, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDombrowski, Damian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFehrenbach, Frank, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFehrenbach, Frank, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGastel, Joris van, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHendrix, Harald, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHills, Helen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKodera, Sergius, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNapoli, J. Nicholas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aThoenes, Christof, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aToscano, Maria, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVecce, Carlo, e